# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: astronomy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea has a nearly spherical shape, with two known craters about 100 and 180 km (62 and 112 mi) in diameter.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Because of its shape and large size, some researchers consider Hygiea a possible dwarf planet.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea has a dark, carbonaceous surface consisting of hydrated and ammoniated silicate minerals, with carbonates and water ice.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea's subsurface likely contains a large fraction of water ice.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] These characteristics make Hygiea very similar to the main-belt dwarf planet Ceres, which suggests the two objects have similar origins and evolutionary histories.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea is the parent body of the Hygiea family, an asteroid family comprising over 7,000 known asteroids that share similar orbital and compositional characteristics with Hygiea.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The Hygiea family is believed to have formed by a giant impact on Hygiea about 2 to 3 billion years ago.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This impact is thought to have shattered Hygiea, which led to its reaccumulation as a nearly spherical body.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea was discovered on the evening of 12 April 1849 by Italian astronomer Annibale de Gasparis at the Astronomical Observatory of Capodimonte in Naples, Italy.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] On that night he was using the observatory's Reichenbach equatorial telescope to observe a section of the sky in the 12th hour of right ascension, as part of his larger project of cataloguing stars along the ecliptic up to the 14th apparent magnitude.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] While comparing his observations to the Berlin Academy's star chart, de Gasparis noticed a starlike object between magnitude 9 and 10 which was not recorded before.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Although poor weather prevented further observations for a few days, de Gasparis reobserved the object on 14 and 17 April and confirmed it had moved between these dates.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Judging by how much the object had moved, de Gasparis concluded it must be another new planet between the orbit of Mars and Jupiter.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] De Gasparis announced his discovery to Erasmo Fabri Scarpellini, secretary of the *Correspondenza Scientifica* bulletin at Rome, Italy, who in turn passed on the news to Heinrich Christian Schumacher, who published it in the *Astronomische Nachrichten* journal on 11 May 1849.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea was the first asteroid discovered by de Gasparis and the tenth asteroid discovered in history.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] He would later discover another six asteroids between 1850 and 1853 and two more during the 1860s.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] De Gasparis invited Ernesto Capocci Belmonte, his friend and director of the Capodimonte Observatory, to assign a name to the asteroid as gratitude for his help and advice.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Capocci suggested the name *Igea*—the Italian spelling of Hygieia, the Greek goddess of health and daughter of Asclepius.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] De Gasparis added the adjective *Borbonica* to Capocci's suggested name, to honor King Ferdinand II of the Bourbons of Naples who ruled the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies and supported the work of the Capodimonte Observatory.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Together, de Gasparis and Capocci proposed the name *Igea Borbonica* ("Bourbon Hygieia") in a letter forwarded to Ferdinand II on 8 May 1849.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] De Gasparis's commemoration of the Bourbons may have helped him and Capocci circumvent punishment for their participation in the liberal movements of 1848.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The name *Igea Borbonica* was not mentioned in the first communications to the European scientific community.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] When English astronomer John Herschel received the news of Hygiea's discovery from his Neapolitan colleagues, he suggested that Parthenope would be an apt name for de Gasparis's discovery, as it comes from the siren who founded Naples in Greek mythology.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Herschel corresponded with other European scientists and astronomers to hear their thoughts on the name Parthenope for de Gasparis's discovery, although by the time he reached out to de Gasparis, Hygiea had already been named one month earlier.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] When Schumacher, editor of *Astronomische Nachrichten*, learned of the name proposed by de Gasparis and Capocci, he complained in a letter addressed to Herschel on 26 June 1849 that it had the Italian spelling instead of the Latin form, as conventionally done for all the other planets.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Regardless, de Gasparis recognized Herschel's suggestion and expressed desire to realize Herschel's wish.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] On 11 May 1850, de Gasparis discovered the asteroid 11 Parthenope and acknowledged Herschel for the name in his announcement.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] There are multiple variations on the Latin spelling of Hygiea, including *Hygièa*, *Hygia*, and *Hygea*.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The modern English form *Hygiea* is a less common variant of the goddess's name, which in Greek is Ὑγίεια (*Hygieia*) or Ὑγεῖα (*Hygeia*).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The name was often spelled *Hygeia* (and occasionally *Hygea*) by astronomers during the early 1850s, though by the 1860s, the spelling *Hygiea* became commonplace.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] According to the English astronomer John Russell Hind, the adjective *Borbonica* had been dropped by 1852.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] As with the other previously discovered asteroids, Hygiea was given an astronomical symbol as a way of representing it.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The serpent, particularly when drinking from a bowl, is a traditional symbol of the goddess Hygieia (cf.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] American astronomer Benjamin Apthorp Gould interpreted Hygiea's symbol as a rod of Asclepius, depicting it as a serpent coiled around a staff in a January 1852 publication of the *Astronomical Journal*: (rod of Asclepius) (U+2695 ⚕).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Both symbols of Hygiea soon became obsolete, as the number of asteroids discovered had grown too much for each to have unique symbols.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] In 1851 Johann Franz Encke proposed a different identification system, suggesting using a number corresponding to the order of discovery enclosed in a small circle—for Hygiea it would be ⑩.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Astronomers began adopting Encke's circled number scheme in scientific publications, though as the number of asteroids discovered grew, astronomers eventually switched to enclosing the number in parentheses, which became the modern minor-planet designation scheme.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] In the case of Hygiea, its modern minor planet designation would be *(10) Hygiea* or *10 Hygiea*.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The Minor Planet Center uses the minor planet provisional designations *A849 GA* and *A900 GA* for Hygiea, though these are only retrospective extensions of the new-style provisional designation scheme established in 1925.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] While the provisional designation A849 GA refers to the discovery date of Hygiea, the designation A900 GA refers to the date when Hygiea was serendipitously observed and catalogued (as *Arequipa 38*) by the Harvard College Observatory's photographic sky survey at Arequipa, Peru in 1900.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea has seen some minor astrological use, though its symbol was confused once again, with Asclepsius's rod replaced by Mercury's caduceus: (Astrological symbol for Hygiea), though in a more elaborate form (U+2BDA ⯚) than the caduceus symbol of the planet Mercury.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The caduceus has long been mistaken for the rod of Asclepius (see caduceus as a symbol of medicine).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea was referred to as a *planet* in the following years after its discovery, though by 1852 astronomers have also called Hygiea a *minor planet* or an *asteroid*.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] These terms were introduced prior to Hygiea's discovery and became more used with the discovery of more asteroids beginning in the 1850s.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] From the second half of the 19th century, asteroids began to be treated in a predominantly collective way, grouped according to orbital or spectral characteristics, with less attention to the individual object.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Since 2019, telescope images have resolved Hygiea's nearly spherical shape, suggesting that it may have reached hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Because Hygiea already orbits the Sun and is located in the asteroid belt where it has not cleared its orbital neighborhood, Hygiea's nearly spherical shape could qualify it as a dwarf planet, according to Pierre Vernazza and collaborators who studied Hygiea with telescope imaging.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] If so, Hygiea could be the smallest dwarf planet known.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] However, the IAU has not yet officially classified Hygiea as a dwarf planet.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea orbits the Sun at an average distance (semi-major axis) of 3.14 astronomical units (AU; 470 million km or 290 million mi), which places it in the outer portion of the main asteroid belt between Mars and Jupiter.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea has an orbital period of 5.57 Earth years and follows an elliptical orbit where its distance from the Sun ranges between 2.79 AU (420 million km; 260 million mi) at perihelion to 3.49 AU (520 million km; 320 million mi) at aphelion.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea has a relatively low orbital inclination of 3.8° with respect to the ecliptic plane.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] In its current orbit, Hygiea never comes closer than 1.24 AU (186 million km; 115 million mi) to Mars and 1.54 AU (230 million km; 143 million mi) to Jupiter.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea is in a three-body mean motion orbital resonance with Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] In this resonance, the mean motions or orbital frequencies of Jupiter, Saturn, and Hygiea follow the relation $8n_{\rm {Jupiter}}-4n_{\rm {Saturn}}-3n_{\rm {Hygiea}}=0$ , where a linear combination of their mean motions ( n ) with integer coefficients equals zero.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Simulations show that this three-body resonance leads to a chaotic evolution in Hygiea's orbit, with a short Lyapunov time between 14,000 and 16,000 years.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This means that changes in Hygiea's orbit become exponentially less predictable over this time scale.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Other asteroids occasionally pass close to Hygiea, sometimes close enough that their trajectories become visibly perturbed or deflected by Hygiea's gravity.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This allows astronomers to measure Hygiea's mass.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] A 2002 study identified 40 known asteroids that have passed within 0.05 AU (7.5 million km; 4.6 million mi) of Hygiea between 1970 and 2000.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Over a time span of 30 million years, Hygiea's gravitational perturbations can cause the proper semi-major axes of close-passing asteroids to change by 0.000908 AU (136,000 km; 84,400 mi).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The Hygiea family is the most populous asteroid family in the outer main belt, and is believed to have formed by a giant impact on Hygiea that ejected at least 1.7% of the asteroid's original mass about 2 to 3 billion years ago.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The impactor that formed the Hygiea family was probably between 75 and 150 km (47 and 93 mi) in diameter.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea contains almost all the mass (over 98%) of the family.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The rotation period of Hygiea is about 13.83 hours (13 hours and 49.5 minutes), with an uncertainty of 0.2 seconds.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This rotation period was determined via direct imaging and analysis of Hygiea's light curve, or changes in brightness over time.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] From Earth, Hygiea's brightness periodically fluctuates by up to 15% from its average value as albedo features on Hygiea's surface rotate in and out of view.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The north pole of Hygiea's rotation axis points toward the ecliptic south, in the direction of ecliptic longitude 306°±3° and ecliptic latitude −29°±3°.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This means Hygiea's rotation axis is highly tilted with an obliquity of 120° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Since Hygiea's obliquity is greater than 90°, it has a retrograde rotation, meaning it rotates backwards with respect to the direction of its orbit around the Sun.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Before it was directly imaged by telescopes in 2017–2018, Hygiea was thought to have a rotation period twice as long as the currently accepted value.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The first measurements of Hygiea's rotation period beginning in the 1950s reported 18 hours while studies from 1991 and onward reported 27.6 hours.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] These past observations did not collect enough datapoints to produce reliable light curves, which led to these inaccurate rotation period measurements.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea is the fourth-largest main-belt asteroid by both volume and mass, with a volume-equivalent mean diameter of 433 ± 8 km (269 ± 5 mi) and a mass of (8.74±0.69)×1019 kg.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Compared to the largest asteroid Ceres, Hygiea is less than half its diameter and is roughly 10% as massive.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea constitutes 3% of the total mass of the entire main belt and is the largest asteroid in the outer main belt.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The four largest asteroids (Ceres, Pallas, Vesta, and Hygiea) together make up a little more than half of the entire main belt's mass.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] These four largest asteroids have sometimes been collectively referred to as the "Big Four" by astronomers, although historically this term meant the first four asteroids discovered (Ceres, Pallas, Juno, and Vesta).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea was not recognized as the fourth-largest asteroid until 1974, when David Morrison measured its diameter and albedo for the first time by using its infrared thermal emission.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The best estimate for Hygiea's diameter was measured via direct imaging using the Very Large Telescope (VLT) in Chile, whose atmospheric turbulence-correcting adaptive optics could resolve the asteroid in high angular resolution.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea's mass was measured by observing how its gravity deflects the paths of other asteroids that pass near it.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This requires an extensive number of observations with accurate positional measurements of the deflected asteroid before and after its close approach.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The measurement of Hygiea's mass through this method was first attempted in 1986, with the analysis of a past close approach by the asteroid 829 Academia (which passed 0.006 AU or 900 thousand km or 560 thousand mi from Hygiea on 19 May 1927).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea's mass has since been refined with additional asteroid close approaches and more accurate observations.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea is a nearly spherical or ellipsoidal object whose diametric dimensions are 450 km × 430 km × 424 km (280 mi × 267 mi × 263 mi), with an uncertainty of ±10 km (6.2 mi) for the equatorial axes and ±20 km (12 mi) for the polar axis.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] It is the second-most spherical main-belt asteroid after Ceres.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The nearly spherical shape of Hygiea suggests it may be in hydrostatic equilibrium, having attained its shape by its own gravity.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Specifically, Hygiea's polar flattening and specific angular momentum closely matches that of a Maclaurin spheroid, which is the shape assumed by a rotating self-gravitating fluid in hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] In contrast to the larger asteroid Vesta, Hygiea lacks large impact craters or basins that would otherwise deform its shape from a sphere.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Only two craters on Hygiea have been confidently identified in VLT imaging, with their respective diameters being 180 ± 15 km (111.8 ± 9.3 mi) and 97 ± 10 km (60.3 ± 6.2 mi).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Both craters appear to have central peaks.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Vernazza and collaborators who studied these images have informally named the larger crater "Serpens" and smaller crater "Calix", after the Latin words for 'snake' and 'cup', respectively.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] These names, which are not approved by the IAU, were chosen because their eponyms commonly appear in symbols of Hygiea.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Besides Serpens and Calix, VLT images of Hygiea show no obvious or bowl-shaped craters larger than 30 km (19 mi) in diameter.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Ceres similarly lacks large bowl-shaped craters and is instead dominated by flat-floored complex craters, which are difficult to see from Earth—this may be the case for Hygiea.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] An abundance of flat-floored craters on Hygiea could indicate a water ice-rich subsurface, which would allow for the relaxation of its surface topography.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Although Hygiea lacks major impact basins, the existence of the Hygiea family points to a major collisional event in its past.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Rather than leaving a giant impact basin like on Vesta, the impact is thought to have completely shattered Hygiea, which erased all of its pre-existing surface features.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Simulations of the giant impact show that most of Hygiea's debris reaccumulated into a fluid-like body, which was able to relax into a sphere by its own gravity.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The present-day shape of Hygiea suggests it solidified around four hours after the impact.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Other large asteroids that are parents of asteroid families, such as 8 Flora and 31 Euphrosyne, have also been found to show roughly spherical shapes and are thus believed to have undergone similar collisional disruption and reaccumulation.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The surface of Hygiea is dark, with an average visual geometric albedo estimated between 6.3% and 7.2%.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The apparent brightness or reflectance varies across Hygiea's surface due to variations in albedo and shadows cast by topographic features.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] VLT images of Hygiea show several bright spots on its surface, with the brightest one located on Hygiea's southern hemisphere at longitude 290° and latitude −30°.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The brightest spot is 10% brighter than the average reflectance of Hygiea's surface.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] A large dark region is present along Hygiea's equator at longitude 60° and latitude 0°, though it is most likely a shadowed region.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The albedo and reflectance variation across Hygiea's surface resembles those of Ceres.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The temperature on Hygiea's surface depends on the asteroid's rotation, distance from the Sun, and the properties of its surface regolith.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] While the surface of Hygiea have been observed to reach temperatures as high as 230 K (−43 °C; −46 °F) at the subsolar point, the surface cools down as it rotates away from the Sun, which averages out the temperature.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Between Hygiea's perihelion and aphelion distances, the average temperature can range from 150 to 180 K (−123 to −93 °C; −190 to −136 °F).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] At Hygiea's semi-major axis, the average temperature would be 163 K (−110 °C; −166 °F).
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Astronomers have described Hygiea as a "fairly dusty object", with a regolith layer consisting mostly of fine dust rather than coarse rock.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This fine regolith has a low thermal inertia, meaning it radiates away heat more easily and leads to cooler temperatures on Hygiea's surface.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The regolith of Hygiea may be dustier (and thus finer) than that of Earth's Moon, which could imply a more mature regolith that has experienced more space weathering.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The regolith layer of Hygiea is estimated to be at least 8 cm (3.1 in) deep.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] These properties of Hygiea's regolith were inferred from the asteroid's lower-than-expected temperature and thermal emission in infrared, submillimetre, and microwave wavelengths.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea is a carbonaceous asteroid whose surface is largely composed of hydrated and ammoniated silicate minerals (phyllosilicates) and carbonates, with hints of water ice.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This composition is inferred from spectroscopic observations of Hygiea, whose visible and near-infrared spectrum characterize it as a C-type asteroid.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] More broadly, it makes Hygiea a member of the C spectral complex, which is common in the outer main belt where Hygiea resides.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The spectrum and composition of Hygiea's surface is very similar to those of carbonaceous chondrite meteorites and Ceres, which has led some astronomers to call Hygiea a "primitive" object and a "virtual spectral twin of Ceres".
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea's resemblance to carbonaceous chondrites (particularly CM chondrites) suggests it shares a similar history of having undergone little thermal alteration and some aqueous alteration of its original minerals, hence its likely primitive nature.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Slight differences between the near-infrared spectra of Hygiea and Ceres indicate they have slightly different concentrations of hydrated and ammoniated minerals.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] High resolution near-infrared spectroscopy by the James Webb Space Telescope has found that Hygiea's phyllosilicates are magnesium-rich and appear to match ammoniated saponite.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Ground-based observations have shown that the near-infrared spectrum of Hygiea varies over time, which implies there is compositional variation across Hygiea's surface.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] A 2011 study by Vladimir Busarev observed Hygiea's spectral type changing between C, B, and F over the course of its rotation, which he interpreted as an indication of local dehydration of Hygiea's surface material, possibly as a result of heating by impacts.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] A 2019 study by Andrew Rivkin and colleagues reported changes in the 3.1 μm absorption feature in Hygiea's near-infrared spectrum over a time scale of years.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] While this absorption feature is often attributed to ammoniated minerals, its variations could also correspond to either hydrated minerals or potentially water ice frost.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Rivkin and colleagues speculated that the variations could be caused by exposed subsurface material on some parts of Hygiea's surface, although they do not appear to be correlated with one particular surface location.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea's bulk density has been estimated as either 1.944±0.250 g/cm3 or 2.06±0.20 g/cm3, based on measurements of its diameter and mass from 2020 and 2021, respectively.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea's bulk density is similar to that of Ceres (2.16 g/cm3), which together with Hygiea's large size suggests it could have a differentiated interior.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea likely has a water ice-rich subsurface, as hinted by Hygiea's bulk density, spectroscopic detections of water ice, and its lack of large, bowl-shaped craters.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] They further speculated that the higher densities of Hygiea and other large C-type asteroids may be due to a more lithified or compacted interior, as a result of significant aqueous alteration.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Despite its size, Hygiea appears very dim when observed from Earth.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] This is due to its dark surface and its position in the outer main belt.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] For this reason, six smaller asteroids were observed before Annibale de Gasparis discovered Hygiea on 12 April 1849.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Although it is the largest body in its region, due to its dark surface and farther-than-average distance from the Sun, Hygiea appears very dim when observed from Earth.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] In fact, it is the third dimmest of the first twenty-three asteroids discovered, with only 13 Egeria and 17 Thetis having lower mean opposition magnitudes.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] At most oppositions, Hygiea has a magnitude of around +10.2, which is as much as four orders fainter than Vesta, and observation calls for at least a 4-inch (100 mm) telescope to resolve.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] However, at a perihelic opposition, Hygiea can reach +9.1 magnitude and may just be resolvable with 10 × 50 binoculars, unlike the next two largest asteroids in the asteroid belt, 704 Interamnia and 511 Davida, which are always beyond binocular visibility.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] A total of 17 stellar occultations by Hygiea have been tracked by Earth-based astronomers, including two (in 2002 and 2014) that were seen by a large number of observers.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The observations have been used to constrain Hygiea's size, shape and rotation axis.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The Hubble Space Telescope has resolved the asteroid and ruled out the presence of any orbiting companions larger than about 16 kilometres (9.9 mi) in diameter.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea has not been explored by any space probe.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Sykes and others from the Planetary Science Institute proposed the *Exploring the Very Earliest Epoch* (EVE) mission to NASA, as part of the Discovery Program.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The proposal, which did not get approved, suggested launching a copy of the *Dawn* probe to Hygiea in October 2011 and arriving to the asteroid via rendezvous in 2021.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] In 2013, Pierre Vernazza and Philippe Lamy proposed the medium-class mission *INSIDER* for the European Space Agency's Space Programme.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The proposal, which also did not get approved, suggested rendezvousing and orbiting around two or three large main-belt asteroids before releasing one or two landers.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] Hygiea and 24 Themis were among the potential targets of the *INSIDER* mission concept.
[src:astronomy/10-hygiea] The exploration of primitive main-belt asteroids like Hygiea could provide clues to the processes that led to the formation of the Solar System.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia is a possible dwarf planet with an estimated diameter of 838±44 km, and a low light curve, implying a nearly spherical shape.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] While older size estimates suggested a low density and highly porous interior, newer measurements calculate a higher density between 1.45 g/cm3 and 1.50±0.12 g/cm3.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] It has a dark gray surface with a neutral color index and an exceptionally low albedo of 0.041±0.004.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This low albedo indicates a lack of geological activity.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Observations by the James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) showed that water ice makes up less than 5% of its surface, detecting both amorphous and crystalline water ice alongside carbon dioxide ice.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] It lacks volatile super-ices like methane, placing it in the "prominent water" (H2O-type) TNO group alongside objects like 307261 Máni and 90482 Orcus.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia has one known moon, Actaea, and their combined system mass is 4.861+0.076 −0.074×1020 kg.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The primary body and its moon form a fully tidally locked system with a synchronous rotation period of 5.49 days, similar to the Pluto–Charon system.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The two bodies will pass directly in front of each other during a rare mutual occultation season starting in 2067.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia was discovered on 22 September 2004 by American astronomers Henry Roe, Michael Brown, and Kristina Barkume at the Palomar Observatory in California, United States.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The discovery observations were formally published in May 2005 in the Minor Planet Electronic Circular (MPEC) 2005-J26.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The object was announced alongside a group of seven new trans-Neptunian objects tracked by the IAU's Minor Planet Center.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] At the time of its initial detection on 22 September, Salacia was recorded with a red-filter apparent magnitude ranging between 20.1 and 20.6.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Following its initial tracking, the object was assigned the provisional designation 2004 SB60.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] While the discovery tracking occurred in 2004, astronomers successfully verified earlier positions of the body through archival precovery images taken at the Siding Spring Observatory (Station 260) dating back to 25 July 1982.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The observation arc of Salacia begins with a precovery observation on 25 July 1982 at the Siding Spring Observatory (Station 260).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Between 2001 and 2003, Salacia was pictured multiple times by the Near-Earth Asteroid Tracking (NEAT) program at Palomar (Station 644) and the Sloan Digital Sky Survey at Apache Point (Station 645).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] After its discovery in 2004, it was observed by the 5-meter Hale Reflector (Station 675) and the 3.5-meter telescope at Mauna Kea (Station 568).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] As of May 2026, a total of 490 observations have been recorded over a period of 37.16 years (13,572 days).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] These observations were made by ground-based and space-based telescopes, such as the Hubble Space Telescope (Station 250).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] More recent tracking was done by the Pan-STARRS 1 survey (Station F51), the Weizmann Astrophysical Observatory (Station M01), and the Pises Observatory (Station 122).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The most recent observation recorded in the Minor Planet Center database was done on 1 November 2025, at F51 – Pan-STARRS 1, Haleakalā.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This minor planet was named after Salacia (/səˈleɪʃə/ *sə-LAY-shə*, Latin: [saˈɫaːkia]), the goddess of salt water, consort of Neptune.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] She is the Roman equivalent of the Greek sea goddess Amphitrite or Tethys.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The object had been assigned its permanent minor planet number (120347) on 16 November 2005, following the precise consolidation of its orbital path data.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The official naming citation was subsequently published on 18 February 2011 in M.P.C.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] 73984, which formally established the name within the International Astronomical Union's minor planet index.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Its moon's name is called Actaea (/ækˈtiːə/; Ancient Greek: Ἀκταία, romanized: *Aktaía*, lit.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] It was from Ancient Greek: ἀκτή, romanized: *akté*, lit.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] 'seashore' or 'rocky shore') being one of the 50 Nereid sea-nymphs, matching the system's marine naming theme.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Planetary symbols are no longer used much in astronomy, so Salacia never received a symbol in the astronomical literature.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Denis Moskowitz, a software engineer who designed most of the dwarf planet symbols, proposed a stylised hippocamp (, formerly ) as the symbol for Salacia; although this symbol is not widely used.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia orbits the Sun at a distance of 37.7–46.7 AU with a semi-major axis of 42.2 AU, finishing its orbit once every 274.0 years.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia is a non-resonant object with a moderate eccentricity of approximately 0.11 and a large inclination of 23.9° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The orbit of Salacia is similar to Pluto's, except for a near opposite longitude of ascending node.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Its current position is near its most northern position above the ecliptic.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia is located in the classical region of the Kuiper belt between 39 and 48 AU from the Sun.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Because it lacks an active orbital resonance with Neptune, it is grouped as a typical member of the classical Kuiper belt population, commonly called "cubewanos".
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] However, Salacia's steep orbital inclination of 23.9° places it within the dynamically "hot" sub-population of the classical belt.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Unlike cold classical objects that formed in place along circular paths, hot classical bodies likely formed closer to the Sun and were scattered outward into highly tilted orbits during the early migration of Neptune.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Astronomers utilize different frameworks to sort these outer Solar System bodies, leading to a long-standing academic debate over Salacia's exact status.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] In the Deep Ecliptic Survey framework by Elliot et al., Salacia is grouped as a scattered–extended object because the system automatically places highly tilted orbits into the scattered categories.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Conversely, Brett Gladman and his team reject this label based on a 10-million-year computer simulation testing orbital stability.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Because Salacia's orbit stays perfectly stable and completely clear of Neptune's gravity during the simulation, Gladman et al. formally classify it as a hot classical Kuiper belt object.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This orbital path also places it near the Haumea collisional family by coincidence; however, tracking and space-based spectral data confirm Salacia is an unrelated background object despite its water-ice rich surface.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Stellar occultations by Salacia happen when it passes in front of a background star, letting scientists measure its precise position, shape, and size profile.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] To make predictions more precise, astronomers map Salacia's orbit using wide-field star catalogs, while a 2015 study identified four potential occultations visible by the James Webb Space Telescope using faint background stars between infrared magnitudes 14 and 16.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Several recorded campaigns have progressively narrowed Salacia's orbital path from an early uncertainty of about 2300 km.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] On 27 December 2018, an event monitored by the LESIA - Observatoire de Paris against a Gaia magnitude 15.5 star captured a 4.8 magnitude drop, significantly refining the orbit from an initial ground-based uncertainty of 4214.9 km.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Following this, a 28 July 2023 occultation captured by the 1.54m Danish Telescope at La Silla recorded a light drop lasting 31.2±0.3 s at a relative speed of 25.24 km/s, providing a direct single-chord surface size measurement of 786.5±7.8 km.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] A rare double stellar occultation was recorded on 17 August 2024, when both Salacia and its moon, Actaea, blocked the same Gaia magnitude 15.9 star within 5 minutes of each other.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Because the initial ground-based path carried a massive uncertainty of 1842.8 km, astronomers used the Hubble Space Telescope under Proposal 17848 to take precise photos beforehand, reducing the uncertainty to just 300 km.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This allowed ground stations to align their telescopes perfectly, recording a sharp 5.0 magnitude drop to measure both bodies, while the RECON network is targeting a future occultation of a magnitude 13.9 star scheduled for 26 January 2027.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia has a very low light curve amplitude of only about 3%, meaning its brightness does not change much as it spins.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Accurate tracking measures this variation at 0.0900±0.0036 magnitudes.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This small change suggests that Salacia is either nearly a perfect sphere or its pole is pointing almost directly at Earth.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] In planetary science, minor light variations can be caused by either an elongated shape or by dark and light spots on a round body.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] An elongated shape would produce a double-peaked light curve with two minimums and maximums per rotation.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Because Salacia's light variations show a single-peaked pattern with only one peak per cycle, astronomers explicitly reject the elongated triaxial ellipsoid shape idea.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Instead, the light curve is entirely driven by uneven albedo variations across its surface, so Salacia is unlikely to be an elongated triaxial ellipsoid, but rather having a nearly spherical shape with small albedo variations across its surface.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] In 2014, early studies estimated that Salacia rotated very fast, once every 6.09–6.5 hours.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] However, a long-term study published in 2025 showed this was a mathematical error called "observational aliasing." Because ground telescopes could only watch Salacia for a few days at a time, the gaps in the data made a slow 5.49-day spin look like a fast 6.5-hour cycle.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The 2025 study analyzed 165 hours of data collected over 16 years.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] By combining ground tracking with images from the Hubble Space Telescope, scientists found that Salacia's 5.49-day rotation exactly matches the time its moon, Actaea, takes to complete one orbit (5.49389±0.00001 d).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This means the two bodies are mutually tidally locked in a "doubly synchronous rotation," always showing the exact same face to each other just like Pluto and Charon.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Before this happened, Salacia likely spun much faster, at around 10 hours per rotation.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Because Actaea is relatively large, its gravitational pull created internal friction that gradually slowed Salacia down.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Computer models show this tidal slowing took only 150 million to 400 million years to finish, meaning the pair has been locked in this balance for billions of years.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Separating the individual light data also revealed features about the moon itself.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] While Salacia shows small brightness changes, Actaea exhibits a very high light curve amplitude of at least 0.95 magnitudes.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This indicates that Actaea either has a highly stretched shape or extreme surface contrasts with large dark and light patches.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This discovery cements the system as only the third confirmed doubly synchronous binary in the trans-Neptunian region, joining Pluto–Charon and Eris–Dysnomia.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] In 2025, the total mass of the Salacia–Actaea system was estimated to be at 4.861+0.076 −0.074×1020 kg, with an average system density of 1.50±0.12 g/cm3 which was estimated in 2019; Salacia itself was estimated to be around 838 km in diameter, which is slightly smaller than Orcus (910+50 −40 km).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia has the lowest albedo of any known large trans-Neptunian object, having an albedo of only 0.041±0.004.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] According to the old estimate from 2017 based on an improved thermophysical modelling, the size of Salacia is slightly larger at around 866 km and its density therefore is slightly lower, being calculated at only 1.26 g/cm3 with the old mass estimate of around (4.38±0.16)×1020 kg.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] At 838±44 km, Salacia belongs to the proposed class of "mid-sized" TNOs between 400 and 1,000 km (250 and 620 mi) in diameter.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] It represents the evolutionary transition between small, low-density TNOs and large, high-density dwarf planets.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] William Grundy and his team originally hypothesized that these mid-sized objects maintain highly porous and unheated interiors because structurally similar bodies like 55637 Uni and 229762 Gǃkúnǁʼhòmdímà exhibit low densities near 1 g/cm³.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Under this framework, Grundy et al. proposed that low-albedo, mid-sized bodies did not undergo internal melting or differentiation like Orcus, Quaoar, and Charon.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] If these estimates are accurate, then Salacia would have a higher density than Orcus (1.4±0.2 g/cm3).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Though its extremely low albedo of 4.1% remains consistent with an ancient surface that lacks the widespread geological activity typical of larger dwarf planets.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Brown considers Salacia nearly certain to be a dwarf planet, placing it at the lower edge of his "nearly certain" ranking tier.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia has a dark gray surface with an extremely low albedo of 0.041±0.004 that was measured by Kiss *et al.* in 2025, and a B-V color index of approximately 0.66±0.06, which is considered a neutral color.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Earlier studies have detected an abundance of water ice of less than 5% on the surface.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] However, astronomers got a much clearer look at the surface on 31 August 2023 using the Near-Infrared Spectrograph (NIRSpec) on the James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Observed under Guaranteed Time Observations program 1191, Salacia was at a heliocentric distance of 45.1 au and a phase angle of 0.94°.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The JWST spectrum showed distinct water-ice absorption bands at 1.5, 2, 3, and between 4–5 μm, with a very sharp drop right at 3 μm.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The specific diagnostic band for crystalline water ice at 1.65 μm is weak and difficult to verify.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This indicates that Salacia's surface has a complex mix of both crystalline and amorphous water ice.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The shape of the absorption features between 4.5–5.0 μm depends heavily on how these two ice phases are mixed and the size of their ice grains.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Because water ice has a very high extinction coefficient at 3 μm, the absorption band at that wavelength is nearly 100% optically saturated.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Minor variations in this saturated band suggest the ice sits in complex vertical layers or uneven mixtures in the upper crust.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] It also detected carbon dioxide ice through its strong ν3 fundamental vibrational band at 4.25 μm.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The spectrum displays a distinct V-shaped CO2 absorption feature that bottoms out at 4.27 μm.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This specific V-shape shows that the carbon dioxide ice is not a pure crystalline layer, but is likely trapped as an amorphous mixture inside the surrounding water ice.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Data from the 2.6–2.8 μm range showed no signatures of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), which space radiation usually creates on pure water ice.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Astronomers also searched for a weaker absorption band at 4.37 μm from the heavier isotope 13CO2, but the data was too noisy to confirm it.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia completely lacks volatile super-ices like methane (CH4) or carbon monoxide (CO).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Its surface escape velocity is only 385–542 m/s, which is too weak to keep solar-heated volatile gases from escaping into space at local temperatures of 30–50 K.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This low gravity explains why Salacia also lacks aliphatic hydrocarbons and complex organic signatures between 3.3–3.6 μm.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] However, because Salacia is larger than the critical geophysical threshold of roughly 500 km, it had enough early radiogenic heating to melt and move its internal water and carbon dioxide ices up to the surface.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This internal evolution explains why Salacia keeps an ice-rich surface despite its low albedo and lack of ongoing cryovolcanism.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Because of these strong water and carbon dioxide ice signatures and lack of complex organics, Salacia is classified as a "prominent water" (H2O-type) TNO under recent taxonomic frameworks.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Other mid to large trans-Neptunian objects such as 307261 Máni, 90482 Orcus and 208996 Achlys also have Salacia's neutral spectrum and has a water ice-rich surface or composition.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] These objects are all classified as "prominent water" (H 2O)-type TNOs according to Wong.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] It was discovered on 21 July 2006 by Keith Noll, Harold Levison, Denise Stephens and William Grundy with the Hubble Space Telescope.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Actaea has a diameter of 393±33 km, making it the fifth-largest known moon of a trans-Neptunian object, after Charon (1212±1 km), Dysnomia (615+60 −50 km), Vanth (442.5±10.2 km), and Ilmarë (403±40 km).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Assuming that Actaea has a density of 0.7 g/cm3, which is thought to be typical that of trans-Neptunian objects' moons, The mass ratio between Actaea and Salacia will be approximately 0.044:1.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] It has an extremely low albedo of 0.021±0.004, which is only half the albedo of Salacia (0.041±0.004).
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The Salacia system has undergone enough tidal evolution to circularize its orbit, which matches the low measured eccentricity.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] The ratio of Actaea's semi-major axis to its primary's Hill radius is 0.0023, making it the tightest out of every known trans-Neptunian binary with a calculated orbit.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Tidal forces transferred angular momentum from Salacia's rotation directly into Actaea's orbit, forcing the moon to push farther away until the distance between the two bodies expanded to its modern value of about 13.2 Salacia radii.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Tidal models show that if Salacia remained an unheated, mixed-up blend of primitive rock and ice, this evolution would have dragged out for nearly 1 billion years.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] However, the system could have synchronized much faster, in about 100 million years, if its interior separated early in its history through an ancient, brief epoch of internal melting.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] This allowed the system to reach its stable, quiet state early in the history of the Solar System, whereas larger, more massive bodies like Eris required nearly 4 billion years to complete their tidal cycles.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Salacia has not been visited by a space probe, though many studies have found it to be a feasible target for future missions.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Planetary scientists advocate for the exploration of large trans-Neptunian objects to provide insights into the formation and evolution of the Solar System.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Several studies have analyzed flyby trajectories to Salacia using planetary gravity assists to reduce flight time.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] A 2019 study by Amanda Zangari and her team showed that a spacecraft launched between 2025 and 2027 could use a single Saturn gravity assist to reach Salacia in 15.4 to 24.2 years, depending on the launch vehicle's power.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] For later windows, Samuel Walters and James Lyne identified a 2031 trajectory that utilizes an unpowered Jupiter gravity assist, allowing a probe to complete its outer Solar System transit in exactly 25 years and arrive at Salacia in February 2056.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Advanced flight frameworks using an Earth and Jupiter gravity assist combination (ΔVEGA-JGA) have also been evaluated.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] A 2021 trajectory survey by James Evans Lyne and colleagues identified a launch window on 15 January 2029 with an 18.4-year transit time, and a second option on 27 February 2042 with an 18.2-year duration.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Multi-target missions involving other outer planets have also been proposed.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Holler and his team found a 2040 mission design that performs a close flyby of Neptune before reaching Salacia in December 2046.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] A separate dual-probe mission analyzed by Anderson et al. proposed launching an 800 kg Salacia flyby probe alongside a Neptune flagship mission on 28 February 2042.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Under this optimized flight plan, the Salacia probe would use a Jupiter gravity assist to complete its transit in 17.6 years, executing its close flyby encounter in October 2059.
[src:astronomy/120347-salacia] Additionally, the feasibility of an orbital capture rendezvous has been studied, with a 2013 university assessment showing options for putting a 100 to 380 kg orbiter into a permanent orbit around Salacia using a Jupiter swingby.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Objects in the size range of 400–1000 km, such as Varda, have likely never compressed into fully solid bodies, let alone differentiated, and so are highly unlikely to be dwarf planets.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] However, density calculations for Varda are ambiguous.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] It is not clear if Varda's density is high enough to compressed into a fully solid body.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Its low albedo is however consistent with a lack of the geological activity that is thought to be typical of dwarf planets.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Varda was discovered in March 2006 by American astronomer Jeffrey A.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Larsen as part of a United States Naval Academy Trident Scholar project.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The discovery was made using survey images originally taken on June 21, 2003, with the 0.9-meter Spacewatch telescope at the Kitt Peak National Observatory near Tucson, Arizona.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Larsen's survey ran for 34 months and covered about 8,000 square degrees of the sky to find slow-moving trans-Neptunian objects.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] To detect these very far bodies, the survey used an automated computer software called SLOSUR, that processed a massive 2 terabytes of imaging data.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] This software used a did multiple-night detection scheme to recognize the movements as slow as 0.012 approximately arcseconds per hour, which makes Varda not being mistaken for just a background star.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] One of Varda's early survey detections happened by accident when astronomers lengthened the telescope's exposure time to re observe a Spacewatch near-Earth asteroid discovery named SW40E6, Varda crossed the exact same field of view.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] At the time, Varda was the only large object discovery made by this program and was thought to be the tenth-largest known classical Kuiper belt object at that time.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] When Varda's discovery was announced under the provisional designation 2003 MW12, its orbit was poorly constrained because it has only been observed a few times.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] This was fixed in February 2006 when astronomers used the Spacewatch II telescope to track the object again and confirm its Orbital path.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] This tracking allowed researchers to look for older observations, known as precovery images.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] And the earliest known precovery images of Varda were found on images taken at the Siding Spring Observatory on 19 March 1980, and it is more than 23 years before the official discovery.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] More older observational images from 1983 to 1994 were taken in Palomar Mountain, while the Near-Earth Asteroid Tracking program detected Varda on 30 May and 7 June 2002, by using faint survey images.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] These older observations extended Varda's observation arc to over two decades, which allowed the Minor Planet Center to calculate its orbit with way more precision.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Following its discovery, Varda was tracked by several sky surveys to improve its orbit calculations.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] From 2010 to 2015, the Pan-STARRS 1 survey at Haleakala regularly observed Varda and recorded its position.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] On 10 September 2018, astronomers used a non-geocentric occultation observation to collect the very precise physical characteristics and orbital characteristics of the Varda-Ilmarë system.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] In August 2020, it was tracked by the Asteroid Terrestrial-impact Last Alert System (ATLAS) on Mauna Loa.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The Zwicky Transient Facility (ZTF) at Palomar Mountain observed Varda again in May 2021, followed by tracking from the Space Surveillance Telescope in June 2022.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] These combined survey observations continued until they stopped at the August 2024, creating a highly accurate and very precise orbital path for Varda.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Before receiving its official name, Varda was known by the provisional designation 2003 MW12.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The Minor Planet Center (MPC) assigned it the permanent minor planet number 174567 on 22 January 2008.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The names for Varda and its moon were announced by the MPC on January 16, 2014.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The object is named after Varda, the queen of the Valar in J.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] According to International Astronomical Union (IAU) guidelines, the discoverer can propose a name to a committee that judges whether it is suitable.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Within Tolkien's legendarium, Varda functions as an "angelic power" or creator deity subordinate to the supreme God Eru Ilúvatar, responsible for shaping the stars to illuminate the world.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Its moon was named Ilmarë, after a chief of the Maiar and Varda's handmaiden.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Because the use of planetary symbols is gone out of popularity in terms of modern astronomy, Varda never received an official symbol in scientific literature.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] So, there is no standard symbol for Varda used by astrologers, though Zane Stein proposed a specific star glyph for Varda ().
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Astronomers have analyzed multiple stellar occultations of Varda to derive its precise size, flattening, albedo, and other physical properties.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The first heavily studied occultation occurred on 10 September 2018, when Varda passed in front of a bright background star, yielding a bunch of positive chords.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The evidence of an atmosphere is also investigated.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] While two predicted events in mid-2022 yielded no ground duration, a series of successful occultations were tracked between 2023 and 2025 across South America, East Asia, Africa, and the Arctic.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Notably, the 11 March 2023 event had a maximum predicted duration of 52.7 seconds, while campaigns on 18 March 2023 and 10 June 2024 recorded separate shadow chords for both Varda and Ilmarë.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] During the 24 December 2025 event, only Varda's shadow crossed Earth for 20.3 seconds, while Ilmarë missed the planet entirely.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Another event was predicted for 17 June 2026 across South America, involving a 16.8 magnitude star at a velocity of 24.91 km/s with an expected geocentric distance of 44.7064 au.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Future campaigns are predicted for 2 July 2027 over South Asia and 17 July 2027 over Greenland and Canada, passing a 17.0 and a 16.6 magnitude star respectively.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Varda orbits the Sun at a distance of 39.5–52.7 AU once every 313.1 years (over 114,000 days; semi-major axis of 46.1 AU).
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Its orbit has an eccentricity of 0.14 and an inclination of 21.5° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] As of November 2019, Varda is 47.5 AU from the Sun.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] It will come to perihelion around November 2096.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] It has been observed 321 times over 23 oppositions, with precovery images back to 1980.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Varda is located in the classical region of the Kuiper belt 39–48 AU from the Sun, and is thus classified as a typical member of a classical Kuiper belt object (also known as a "cubewano").
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The high orbital inclination of Varda makes it a dynamically "hot" member of the classical Kuiper belt.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The hot classical Kuiper belt objects are believed to have been scattered by Neptune's gravitational influence during the Solar System's early history.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Varda has a highly flattened, triaxial ellipsoid shape with body dimensions of 778 × 706 × 496 km, derived from a best-fit model with radii of 389 × 353 × 248 km.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Because Earth views Varda nearly pole-on (looking straight down its short c-axis), its shape looks circular from our perspective, which hid its true elongation in earlier observations.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] This larger body volume means Varda's true bulk density is much higher than older estimates, rising to between 1.9 g/cm³.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Varda's long axis is directed toward its moon, Ilmarë.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The chance for this alignment to happen by accident is calculated to be 2%, strongly suggesting that Varda has a triaxial ellipsoid shape.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] However, the published data are not able to fully constrain its three-dimensional shape.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] On 10 September 2018, Varda's projected diameter was previously measured to be 766±6 km via a stellar occultation, with a projected oblateness of 0.066±0.047.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The rotation period of Varda is not fully certain; past estimates include 4.76, 5.91 (the most likely value), or 7.87 hours, or double those values.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Its geometric albedo is measured at 0.099, making its surface as dark as the large plutino 208996 Achlys.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] However, this albedo could already be outdated since newer studies measured a smaller diameter.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The surfaces of both Varda and Ilmarë appear red in visible and near-infrared light (spectral class IR), and Ilmarë is slightly redder.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Light spectrum measurements show signs of methanol ice on the surface, but no clear signs of water ice.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Varda is classified as a CO 2-type ("double-dip") trans-Neptunian object.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Under the assumption that Varda is rotating synchronously once every every 5.75 days, this rotational speed is not fast enough to naturally cause its highly elongated shape under the standard hydrostatic equilibrium, this would require an even faster 4.5-hour period.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] So, astronomers have also considered that Varda has a non-hydrostatic equilibrium shape, theorising that the ellipticity of Varda's limb could represent a "fossil bulge" that froze into place early in its history when Varda was spinning even faster, similar to Quaoar.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] If Varda's interior is not very uniform, then this triaxial shape could also be held together by internal friction and uneven density distributions inside of Varda.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Varda has one known satellite, **Ilmarë**, formal designation **(174567) Varda I**.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Ilmarë was discovered by Keith Noll in 2009, at a separation of about 0.12 arcsec, using discovery images taken by the Hubble Space Telescope on 26 April 2009, the discovery was reported in 2011.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Ilmarë has a low albedo of 0.068±0.011 and is approximately 403 km in diameter according to the ALMA study done in 2025, making it the fourth-largest known moon of a trans-Neptunian object, after Charon, Dysnomia, and Vanth.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Under the assumption of a lower density of 0.7 g/cm3, which is thought to be more typical that of trans-Neptunian objects in the ~400 km size range, the Ilmarë-to-Varda mass ratio would be around 0.11:1.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Even if Ilmarë has the same density as Varda at 1.15 g/cm3, the mass ratio would be relatively high at 0.16:1.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] This makes it one of the systems with the largest known mass ratios, with the mass ratio being quite similar to Pluto-Charon or Orcus-Vanth.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Ilmarë orbits Varda at a distance of 4815±29 km and an eccentricity of 0.016±0.004 respectively.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Ilmarë has an orbital period of approximately 5.750824±0.000016 d.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Ilmarë's orbit has an inclination of 77.4±1.9° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Observations from a 2018 stellar occultation show that Varda's longest equatorial axis points almost directly toward its moon Ilmarë.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Varda's elongated axis has a position angle of 67°±8°, while Ilmarë is located at a position angle of 60.8°±0.7°.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] If Varda were not tidally locked, the chance of this very close alignment happening is only around 2%.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Furthermore, the large size ratio between Varda and its moon Ilmarë strongly suggests that tidal synchronization should happen really quickly, especially at the small semi-major axis of the binary, similar to the Salacia-Actaea system.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] This alignment is almost matches the minimum energy state expected for a tidally evolved binary system.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] A study has analyzed flyby trajectories to Varda using planetary gravity assists to reduce travel time.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] A second Jupiter-only window opens between 2039 and 2040, giving a steady flight duration of about 10.9 years.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] The spacecraft would reach Varda at a distance of 40.8 to 44.0 AU from the Sun; Jupiter–Saturn pathways: A multi-planet flyby window opens between 2037 and 2040.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] In a modeled 2038 flight path, a spacecraft launched on November 4, 2038, would fly past Jupiter on April 17, 2040, and Saturn on December 5, 2041, before arriving at Varda on September 26, 2053.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Adding a Saturn flyby actually makes the trip to Varda longer than taking a direct path using only Jupiter.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Skipping Saturn saves more than 10 years of travel time in some flights.
[src:astronomy/174567-varda] Any future mission would also fly past Varda's moon, Ilmarë, at a high speed of about 16.3 km/s.
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] Chambers, observing for the Pan-STARRS project.
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] As of September 2014, it has been observed 21 times with a data-arc span of 26 days.
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] It is an Aten asteroid and its semi-major axis (0.7235 astronomical units; AU) is very similar to that of Venus but it has a high eccentricity (0.6115) and a small orbital inclination (4.794°).
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] With an absolute magnitude of 24.1, it has a diameter in the range 40–100 m (for an assumed albedo range of 0.04–0.20).
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] 2013 ND15 has been identified as a Venus trojan following a tadpole orbit around Venus's Lagrangian point L4.
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] Besides being a Venus co-orbital, this asteroid is also a Mercury crosser and an Earth crosser.
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] 2013 ND15 exhibits resonant (or near-resonant) behavior with Mercury, Venus and Earth.
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] Its short-term dynamical evolution is different from that of the other three Venus co-orbitals, 2001 CK32, Zoozve, and 2012 XE133.
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] 2013 ND15 is not included in the Minor Planet Center list of potentially hazardous asteroids (PHAs) because its absolute magnitude is greater than 22.0, even though it comes to within 0.05 AU of Earth periodically.
[src:astronomy/2013-nd15] It approached Earth at 0.077 AU on 21 June 2016.
[src:astronomy/2019-uo14] Before Saturn captured 2019 UO14, it was floating around the Solar System as a centaur.
[src:astronomy/2019-uo14] 2,000 years ago, Saturn trapped the centaur in its L4 point, making it into a trojan.
[src:astronomy/2019-uo14] However, due to continuous pulling from Jupiter and Uranus, eventually 2019 UO14 will be ejected from its trojan orbit.
[src:astronomy/2019-uo14] It is suggested that there will be more Saturnian trojans to be discovered, since Saturn has a large gravitational pull.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Although it was initially called an asteroid and classified only as a minor planet with the designation "2060 Chiron", in 1989 it was found to exhibit behavior typical of a comet.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Today it is classified as both a minor planet and a comet, and is accordingly also known by the cometary designation **95P/Chiron**.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] More recently, a series of occultation events through the 2010s and early 2020s revealed that Chiron hosts rings, making it one of four minor planets known to have rings (the three others being 10199 Chariklo, Haumea, and Quaoar) and the only known comet to do so.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron was discovered on 1 November 1977 by Charles Kowal from images taken on 18 October at Palomar Observatory.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] It was given the temporary designation of 1977 UB.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] It was found near aphelion and at the time of discovery it was the most distant-known minor planet.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron was even claimed as the tenth planet by the press.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron was later found on several precovery images, going back to 1895, which allowed its orbit to be accurately determined.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] It had been at perihelion in 1945 but was not discovered then because there were few searches being made at that time, and these were not sensitive to slow-moving objects.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The Lowell Observatory's survey for distant planets would not have gone down faint enough in the 1930s and did not cover the right region of the sky in the 1940s.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The April 1895 precovery image was one month after the March 1895 perihelion.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] This minor planet was named after Chiron, a half-human, half-horse centaur from Greek mythology.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Son of the Titan Cronus and the nymph Philyra, Chiron was the wisest and most just of all centaurs, serving as an instructor of the Greek heroes.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The official naming citation was published by the Minor Planet Center on 1 April 1978 (M.P.C.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] It was suggested that the names of other centaurs be reserved for objects of the same type.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron, along with most major and minor planetary bodies, is not generally given a symbol in astronomy.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] A symbol, (⚷), was devised for it by Al H.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Morrison and is mostly used among astrologers: it resembles a key as well as an OK monogram for **O**bject **K**owal.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron's orbit was found to be highly eccentric (0.37), with perihelion just inside the orbit of Saturn and aphelion just outside the perihelion of Uranus (it does not reach the average distance of Uranus, however).
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] According to the program Solex, Chiron's closest approach to Saturn in modern times was around May 720, when it came within 30.5±2.0 million km (0.204 ± 0.013 AU) of the planet.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] During this passage Saturn's gravity caused Chiron's semi-major axis to decrease from 14.55±0.12 AU to 13.7 AU.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron's orbit does not intersect Uranus' orbit.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron attracted considerable interest because it was the first object discovered in such an orbit, well outside the asteroid belt.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron is classified as a centaur, the first of a class of objects orbiting between the outer planets.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron is a Saturn–Uranus object because its perihelion lies in Saturn's zone of control and its aphelion lies in that of Uranus.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Centaurs are not in stable orbits and will be removed by gravitational perturbation by the giant planets over a period of millions of years, moving to different orbits or leaving the Solar System altogether.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron likely comes from the Kuiper belt and will probably become a short-period comet in about a million years.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron came to perihelion (closest point to the Sun) in 1996 and aphelion in May 2021.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The visible and near-infrared spectrum of Chiron is neutral, and is similar to that of C-type asteroids and the nucleus of Halley's Comet.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The near-infrared spectrum of Chiron shows absence of water ice.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The infrared spectrum, however, from 0.97 to 5.27 μm, as revealed by the James Webb Space Telescope reveals the presence of gas in the coma and a diverse inventory of ices, on the surface or in the coma.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Absorption bands of carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide, ethane, propane, and acetylene were detected, together with water ice in its amorphous state.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] A key finding was the detection of fluorescent methane emissions, providing the first evidence of a gas coma rich in this compound.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Gaseous carbon dioxide emission was also identified in the fundamental stretching band at 4.27 μm.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The authors argue that the presence of methane emission is the first proof of the desorption of methane due to a density phase transition of amorphous water ice at low temperature (61 K) previously studied in the laboratory.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Four rotational light curves of Chiron were taken from photometric observations between 1989 and 1997.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Lightcurve analysis gave a concurring, well-defined rotational period of 5.918 hours with a small brightness variation of 0.05 to 0.09 magnitude, which indicates that the body has a rather spheroidal shape (U=3/3/3).
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The assumed size of an object depends on its absolute magnitude (H) and the albedo (the amount of light it reflects).
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] In 1984 Lebofsky estimated Chiron to be about 180 km in diameter.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Estimates in the 1990s were closer to 150 km in diameter.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Occultation data from 1993 suggests a diameter of about 180 km.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Combined data from the Spitzer Space Telescope in 2007 and the Herschel Space Observatory in 2011 suggests that Chiron is 218±20 km in diameter.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Therefore, Chiron may be as large as 10199 Chariklo.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The diameter of Chiron is difficult to estimate in part because the true absolute magnitude of its nucleus is uncertain due to its highly variable cometary activity.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] In February 1988, at 12 AU from the Sun, Chiron brightened by 75 percent.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] This is behavior typical of comets but not asteroids.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Further observations in April 1989 showed that Chiron had developed a cometary coma, A tail was detected in 1993.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron differs from other comets in that water is not a major component of its coma, because it is too far from the Sun for water to sublimate.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] In 1995 carbon monoxide was detected in Chiron in very small amounts, and the derived CO production rate was calculated to be sufficient to account for the observed coma.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Cyanide was also detected in the spectrum of Chiron in 1991.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] At the time of its discovery, Chiron was close to aphelion, whereas the observations showing a coma were done closer to perihelion, perhaps explaining why no cometary behavior had been seen earlier.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The fact that Chiron is still active probably means it has not been in its current orbit very long.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron is officially designated as both a comet—95P/Chiron—and a minor planet, an indication of the sometimes fuzzy dividing line between the two classes of object.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The term proto-comet has also been used.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Being about 220 km in diameter, it is unusually large for a comet nucleus.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron was the first member of a new family of Chiron-type comets (CTC) with (TJupiter > 3; a > aJupiter).
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Other CTCs include: 39P/Oterma, 165P/LINEAR, 166P/NEAT, and 167P/CINEOS.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] There are also non-centaur asteroids that are simultaneously classified as comets, such as 4015 Wilson–Harrington, 7968 Elst–Pizarro, and 118401 LINEAR.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Since the discovery of Chiron, other centaurs have been discovered, and nearly all are currently classified as minor planets, but are being observed for possible cometary behavior.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] 60558 Echeclus has displayed a cometary coma and now also has the cometary designation 174P/Echeclus.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] After passing perihelion in early 2008, 52872 Okyrhoe significantly brightened.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Chiron has rings, similar to the better-established rings of 10199 Chariklo.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The rings' changing appearance at different viewing angles can largely explain the long-term variation in Chiron's brightness and hence estimates of Chiron's albedo and size.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Moreover, it can, by assuming that the water ice is in Chiron's rings, explain the changing intensity of the infrared water-ice absorption bands in Chiron's spectrum, including their disappearance in 2001 (when the rings were edge-on).
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Also, the geometric albedo of Chiron's rings as determined by spectroscopy is consistent with that used to explain Chiron's long-term brightness variations.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Further evidence of the rings was provided by two independent observations of occultations on 28 November 2018 and 15 December 2022, which suggests that their structure is constantly evolving.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] In the 2018 event Chiron's rings were observed to have less material than in 2011, but seemed to be developing a partial third ring; by the 2022 event there was more material than either of the previous observations, and the third ring had become fully developed.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Ortiz speculated that the extra material in the 2022 event could be from an outburst observed in 2021, which left more material in orbit and thus bolstered the generation of the third ring—this is also expected to be cyclical, maintaining the rings.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The preferred pole of Chiron's rings is, in ecliptic coordinates, *λ* = 151°±8°, *β* = 18°±11°.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The rings' width, separation, and optical depths were observed to be nearly identical to those of Chariklo's rings until the 2018 observation, indicating that the same type of structure had been responsible for both.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Moreover, both their rings are within their respective Roche limits, though Chiron's newly developed third ring may be outside of it depending on its density.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] The *Chiron Orbiter Mission* was a mission proposed for NASA's New Frontiers program or Flagship program.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] It was published in May 2010 and proposed an orbiter mission to Chiron.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] Its launch date could have varied from as early as 2023 to as late as 2025, depending on budget and propulsion type.
[src:astronomy/2060-chiron] There was another mission proposed, part of the Discovery Program known as *Centaurus*; if approved, it would have launched between 2026 and 2029 and made a flyby of 2060 Chiron and one other centaur sometime in the 2030s.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The surface of Achlys is dark gray and mostly composed of water ice.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Observations of stellar occultations show that Achlys's surface bears a chasm or depression between 8 and 13 km (5.0 and 8.1 mi) deep, similar to those seen on Pluto and its moon Charon.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys has one known moon that is about 80 km (50 mi) in diameter.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The mass and density of Achlys has not been measured, though predictions based on its shape and rotation suggest that it has a density lower than that of water ice.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys was discovered on 13 January 2003 by astronomers Chad Trujillo and Michael Brown at Palomar Observatory in San Diego County, California.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] At the time, Trujillo and Brown were searching the sky for bright and large trans-Neptunian objects—Solar System objects beyond Neptune—using the Palomar Observatory's 1.22-meter (48 in) Samuel Oschin telescope, as part of their "Caltech Wide Area Sky Survey" project.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Their sky survey had been operating jointly with Palomar's Near Earth Asteroid Tracking (NEAT) program since 2001 and was responsible for the discovery of several other large trans-Neptunian objects including Quaoar.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys was found through manual vetting of potential moving objects identified by Trujillo and Brown's automated image-searching software.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] It was detected at a red-filter apparent magnitude of 20.2.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The discovery of Achlys was announced by Minor Planet Center (MPC) on 26 January 2003.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Since then, numerous precovery observations of Achlys were identified from Palomar Observatory, with observations from 2001–2002 reported in April 2003 and a single observation from 19 March 1996 reported in December 2007.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] This 1996 observation is the earliest known precovery of Achlys, predating its discovery by over six years.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] This object is named after Achlys, the goddess of sorrow and grief in the ancient Greek epic poem *Shield of Heracles*.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] In Homer's *Iliad*, "achlys" also refers to the mist that covers the eyes of the dying.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] This name follows the theme of mythological figures related to the underworld, which is required for plutinos by the International Astronomical Union (IAU).
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The object was officially named Achlys on 30 June 2025 by the IAU's Working Group for Small Body Nomenclature.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Before Achlys was named, it was known by its provisional designation 2003 AZ84, which was given by the MPC in its discovery announcement.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] This provisional designation encodes the year and half-month of Achlys's discovery date.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys's minor planet catalog number of 208996 was given by the MPC on 11 March 2009.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] While moving across the sky, Achlys occasionally passes in front of a background star and briefly blocks out its light from Earth, resulting in a stellar occultation.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] When observed at different locations, stellar occultations by Achlys can reveal fine details that are unresolvable to telescope imaging, such as its size, shape, and potential surrounding features such as rings and moons.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The first successful detection of a stellar occultation by Achlys was reported by a single observer from Chile on 8 January 2011.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Later observations of stellar occultations on 3 February 2012 and 15 November 2014 were successfully detected by multiple observers at different locations, which revealed the elongated shape and topography of Achlys for the first time.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] No rings and moons were detected around Achlys in these observations.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys orbits the Sun at a semi-major axis or average distance of 39.5 astronomical units (AU), which places it beyond the orbit of Neptune (30.1 AU) and in the inner reaches of the Kuiper belt, where many other small objects reside.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The location of Achlys's orbit makes it a trans-Neptunian object (TNO) and a Kuiper belt object.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys completes one orbit about every 247 years, which puts it in a 2:3 mean-motion orbital resonance with Neptune.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] That is, Achlys completes two orbits around the Sun for every three orbits completed by Neptune.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Many other Kuiper belt objects, including the dwarf planet Pluto, share Achlys's 2:3 resonance with Neptune—these objects are classified as plutinos.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys is the third largest plutino, after Pluto and Orcus.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The orbit of Achlys is elliptical and inclined with respect to the ecliptic by 13.6°.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Unlike some plutinos including Pluto, Achlys does not cross Neptune's orbit: its elliptical orbit brings it as close as 32.4 AU from the Sun (at perihelion) to as far as 46.5 AU from the Sun (at aphelion).
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys previously passed aphelion in June 1982 and will come to perihelion in March 2107.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Even though Achlys's orbit is perturbed by the gravitational influence of other planets, the perihelion of Achlys's orbit is not expected to drop below 31.6 AU in the next 10 million years, according to *N*-body simulations by the Deep Ecliptic Survey.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys's orbit is stable over several billion years and is unlikely to change significantly over the remaining life of the Solar System.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Observations of stellar occultations from 2012 and 2014 show that Achlys is an elongated object.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Under the assumption that Achlys is in hydrostatic equilibrium (that is, its shape is controlled by its own gravity and rotation), its shape can be approximated by a rotationally distorted Jacobi ellipsoid with dimensions of 940 km × 766 km × 490 km (584 mi × 476 mi × 304 mi).
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] With these dimensions, the equatorial diameter of Achlys is roughly twice as long as its polar diameter.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] This rotationally distorted shape has been seen in other large Kuiper belt objects, like Haumea and Varuna.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The approximated dimensions of Achlys translate to an area-equivalent diameter of 772 km (480 mi), which is large enough that astronomers consider Achlys likely in hydrostatic equilibrium and therefore a possible dwarf planet.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys is among the top 30 largest known TNOs.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The mass and density of Achlys have not been measured, though the assumption of hydrostatic equilibrium with its ellipsoidal shape predicts that it should have a density in the range of 0.85–1.12 g/cm3, with the most likely value being 0.87 g/cm3.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] This density indicates Achlys has a mass of around 2×1020 kg.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys falls within the 400–1,000 km (250–620 mi) diameter range where TNOs are typically observed with densities lower than that of water ice (1 g/cm3); these objects are theorized to have porous interior structures due to a lack of internal melting, differentiation, and gravitational compression.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys's small size also makes it unlikely to hold much internal heat or possess cryovolcanism.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys has a rotation period of about 6.79 hours.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The apparent brightness of Achlys periodically fluctuates with a small peak-to-peak amplitude of 0.07 magnitudes as it rotates, which could be monitored by telescopes on Earth.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The rotation period of Achlys was first measured by Scott Sheppard and David C.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Jewitt in 2003, who found a rotation period of either 6.7 and 13.4 hours.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The rotation period of Achlys remained ambiguous until 2017, when it was found to have an elongated shape that was best explained by the former period.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys has a highly tilted rotation axis that is pointed somewhat toward Earth, according to observations of Achlys's small rotational brightness variation, constant thermal emission, and variable projected shape in stellar occultations.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] A 2017 analysis of stellar occultation observations from 2012 and 2014 suggested that Achlys's rotational pole could be oriented at an opening angle of roughly 50° with respect to the plane of the sky and at a position angle of 78° eastward from the celestial north pole.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys is a dark, icy object with a likely ancient surface devoid of geological activity.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Its surface is dominated by water ice and has a low, average geometric albedo of about 10%.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Astronomical spectroscopy has shown that both amorphous and crystalline forms of water ice are present on Achlys's surface, which make it highly absorbent in near-infrared wavelengths of light.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Crystalline water ice is not commonly found on the surfaces of TNOs due to their cold temperatures, so its presence on Achlys suggests that the object had experienced heating, possibly by an impact event.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Spectroscopic analyses from 2010 and 2011 suggest that Achlys's surface may be darkened by amorphous carbon, which is thought to originate from heavily irradiated organic compounds.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] These analyses also suggest that water ice and amorphous carbon each comprise major portions of Achlys's surface, with amorphous water ice likely more abundant than crystalline water ice.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The surface of Achlys is devoid of volatile ices like nitrogen and carbon monoxide, in contrast to the largest trans-Neptunian objects like Pluto.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] This is expected because Achlys's gravity is too weak to hold on any atmosphere, especially volatiles after they have sublimated into vapor.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] In visible light, Achlys's surface is spectrally neutral with respect to the Sun, which gives it a gray color.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys shares its gray color and water ice-rich surface with several TNOs including the large plutino Orcus; these objects are classified as BB ("blue")-type TNOs in terms of visible color and "prominent water" (H 2O)-type TNOs in terms of spectra.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The gray color of Achlys implies that it contains little amounts of tholins—moderately irradiated organic compounds that would otherwise tint the surface red.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Spectroscopic analyses suggest that tholins should make up roughly 10% of Achlys's surface composition.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The albedo is suspected to vary across Achlys's surface because the object varies in brightness as it rotates.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Near-infrared spectroscopy of Achlys shows variable spectral absorption of water ice and tentative signs of methanol ice.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Visible-light spectroscopy has detected sporadic hints of hydrated minerals such as silicates, which are suspected to exist in localized deposits on Achlys's surface.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The color of Achlys has been observed to change as it rotates, with its visible spectral slope or redness varying between 3.5%/0.1 μm and 8.5%/0.1 μm.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] This color variation may hint at localized areas of concentrated tholins on Achlys's surface, which could be explained by various phenomena such as an impact crater left by a red TNO.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] In November 2014, an observation of a stellar occultation from Yunnan, China revealed that Achlys has a topographic feature located at its limb—the edge of its projected shape.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The observation showed a gradual dimming of the occulted star, which has been interpreted as a partial, grazing occultation by Achlys's topographic feature.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys is the first TNO whose topographic feature has been observed via stellar occultation.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The topographic feature on Achlys could either be a chasm at least 7.7 km (4.8 mi) deep and roughly 22.6 km (14.0 mi) wide, or a shallow-sloped depression roughly 13.4 km (8.3 mi) deep and at least 80 km (50 mi) wide.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Such features have been seen on Pluto and its moon Charon.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys has one known natural satellite or moon, which has no official name or designation.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Brown and Terry-Ann Suer in images taken by the Hubble Space Telescope on 2 December 2005.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The discovery of Achlys's moon was announced on 22 February 2007 via an International Astronomical Union Circular published by the Central Bureau for Astronomical Telegrams.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The moon of Achlys has not been seen since its discovery.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The lack of redetections means that the orbit of Achlys's moon could not be determined, which prevents an accurate determination of Achlys's mass.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Nevertheless, some properties of the moon's orbit have been predicted based on its observed separation distance from Achlys at discovery.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] In the discovery images, the moon was seen at an angular separation of 0.22±0.01 arcseconds from Achlys, which translates to an apparent distance of at least 7,200 ± 300 km (4,470 ± 190 mi).
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] If this separation distance is the moon's semi-major axis from Achlys, then it would have an orbital period of approximately 12 days.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The moon is predicted to have a non-circular orbit due to weak tidal circularization by Achlys.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] The moon is 5.0±0.3 magnitudes fainter than Achlys, which translates to a diameter of roughly 80 km (50 mi) if it has the same albedo as Achlys.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] If the moon has an icy composition, its mass would be a few times 1017 kg.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Compared to other TNOs with moons, the moon of Achlys is quite small; this suggests that Achlys's moon formed from a collision with another body.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] A 2026 study led by José Gómez-Limón found that Achlys emits more thermal radiation than expected for its size, which could be explained if there is additional thermal radiation coming from its moon.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] However, to explain Achlys's excess thermal emission, its moon would have to be much larger with a diameter of 236+64 −52 km (147+40 −32 mi).
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] If this large diameter estimate is accurate, then it would imply the moon has significantly different surface properties (such as albedo) from Achlys.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] On the other hand, if Achlys's moon is much smaller, then the excess thermal emission can be explained if Achlys has either a larger diameter or a second moon.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Achlys has not been visited by a space probe, though various studies have found it to be a feasible target for future missions.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Planetary scientists advocate for the exploration of large TNOs like Achlys because they can provide insights into the formation and evolution of the Solar System.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] A 2019 study by Amanda Zangari and collaborators identified several possible flyby trajectories to Achlys, using different excess launch energies and gravity assists from planets.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] A spacecraft launched in 2035–2038 could use a single Jupiter gravity assist to reach Achlys in 8.2–11.6 years.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Alternatively, a spacecraft launched in 2025–2034 could use a single Saturn gravity assist to reach Achlys in 9.2–18.2 years.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] A 2037–2038 launch trajectory using gravity assists from both Jupiter and Saturn would be less efficient however, as it would demand higher launch energies with long mission durations of 23.8–23.9 years.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Flyby missions to Achlys using gravity assists from Uranus are also possible.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] A 2021 study by Bryan Holler and colleagues for the 2023–2032 Planetary Science Decadal Survey identified Achlys as a potential target for a flyby mission to Uranus, which could launch in the 2030s, reach Uranus in 2045, and then reach Achlys in 2049.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] Zangari and collaborators found that a spacecraft launched in 2034–2038 could reach Achlys in 13.1–13.2 years via gravity assists from both Jupiter and Uranus, whereas a spacecraft launched in 2027–2033 could reach Achlys in 17.7 years via gravity assists from both Jupiter and Uranus.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] A 2013 study by the University of Tennessee investigated the possibility of sending a small (100–380 kg) orbiter spacecraft to a TNO and found that Achlys could be a feasible option.
[src:astronomy/208996-achlys] An orbiter launched in July 2035 or 2047 could make use of a Jupiter gravity assist to reach Achlys in 10–25 years depending on the excess launch energy, though lower launch energies and longer mission durations are required to make it possible for orbit insertion around Achlys.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astronomy is one of the oldest natural sciences.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The early civilizations in recorded history made methodical observations of the night sky.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] These include the Egyptians, Babylonians, Greeks, Indians, Chinese, Maya, and many ancient indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In the past, astronomy included disciplines as diverse as astrometry, celestial navigation, observational astronomy, and the making of calendars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astronomy is one of the few sciences in which amateurs play an active role.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] This is especially true for the discovery and observation of transient events.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Amateur astronomers have helped with many important discoveries, such as finding new comets.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] "Astronomy" and "astrophysics" are broadly synonymous in modern usage.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Sometimes, as in the introduction of the introductory textbook *The Physical Universe* by Frank Shu, "astronomy" means the qualitative study of the subject, whereas "astrophysics" is the physics-oriented version of the subject.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Some fields, such as astrometry, are in this sense purely astronomy rather than also astrophysics.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Research departments may use "astronomy" and "astrophysics" according to whether the department is historically affiliated with a physics department, and many professional astronomers have physics rather than astronomy degrees.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Thus, in modern use, the two terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The initial development of astronomy was driven by practical needs like agricultural calendars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Before recorded history archeological sites such as Stonehenge provide evidence of ancient interest in astronomical observations.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Evidence also comes from artefacts such as the Nebra sky disc inlaid with symbols interpreted as a sun, moon, and stars including a cluster of seven stars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Megalithic structures located in Nabta Playa, Upper Egypt featured astronomical calendar arrangements in alignment with the heliacal rising of Sirius and supported calibration the yearly calendar for the annual Nile flood.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Civilizations such as Egypt, Mesopotamia, Greece, India, China independently but with cross-cultural influences created astronomical observatories and developed ideas on the nature of the Universe, along with calendars and astronomical instruments.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] A key early development was the beginning of mathematical and scientific astronomy among the Babylonians, laying the foundations for astronomical traditions in other civilizations.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The Babylonians discovered that lunar eclipses recurred in the saros cycle of 223 synodic months.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Following the Babylonians, significant advances were made in ancient Greece and the Hellenistic world.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Greek astronomy sought a rational, physical explanation for celestial phenomena.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In the 4th century BC, Heracleides Ponticus was the first to proposed that the Earth rotates on its own axis.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos estimated the size and distance of the Moon and Sun, and he proposed a model of the Solar System where the Earth and planets rotated around the Sun, now called the heliocentric model.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In the 2nd century BC, Hipparchus calculated the size and distance of the Moon and invented the earliest known astronomical devices such as the astrolabe.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] He also observed the small drift in the positions of the equinoxes and solstices with respect to the fixed stars that we now know is caused by precession.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Hipparchus also created a catalog of 1020 stars, and most of the constellations of the northern hemisphere derive from Greek astronomy.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] 150–80 BC) was an early analog computer designed to calculate the location of the Sun, Moon, and planets for a given date.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Technological artifacts of similar complexity did not reappear until the 14th century, when mechanical astronomical clocks appeared in Europe.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] After the classical Greek era, astronomy was dominated by the geocentric model of the Universe, or the Ptolemaic system, named after Claudius Ptolemy.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] His 13-volume astronomy work, named the *Almagest* in its Arabic translation, became the primary reference for over a thousand years.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In this system, the Earth was believed to be the center of the Universe with the Sun, the Moon and the stars rotating around it.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] While the system would eventually be discredited, it gave the most accurate predictions for the positions of astronomical bodies available at that time.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] With the arrival of Hellenistic astronomy in India through trade and cultural contacts, Indian astronomy entered a new phase during the early centuries CE.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In the later medieval period, the Kerala school contributed to astronomy through refined observational practices and more accurate planetary and eclipse calculations.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astronomy flourished in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astronomical observatories were established there by the early 9th century.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In 964, the Andromeda Galaxy, the largest galaxy in the Local Group, was described by the Persian Muslim astronomer Abd al-Rahman al-Sufi in his *Book of Fixed Stars*.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The SN 1006 supernova, the brightest apparent magnitude stellar event in the last 1000 years, was observed by the Egyptian Arabic astronomer Ali ibn Ridwan and Chinese astronomers in 1006.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Iranian scholar Al-Biruni observed that, contrary to Ptolemy, the Sun's apogee (highest point in the heavens) was mobile, not fixed.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Arabic astronomers introduced many Arabic names now used for individual stars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The ruins at Great Zimbabwe and Timbuktu may have housed astronomical observatories.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In Post-classical West Africa, astronomers studied the movement of stars and relation to seasons, crafting charts of the heavens and diagrams of orbits of the other planets based on complex mathematical calculations.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Songhai historian Mahmud Kati documented a meteor shower in 1583.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Nicole Oresme (1320–1382) discussed evidence for the rotation of the Earth.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Jean Buridan (1300–1361) developed the theory of impetus, describing motions including of the celestial bodies.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] For over six centuries (from the recovery of ancient learning during the late Middle Ages into the Enlightenment), the Roman Catholic Church gave more financial and social support to the study of astronomy than probably all other institutions.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Among the Church's motives was finding the date for Easter.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] During the Renaissance, Nicolaus Copernicus proposed a heliocentric model of the solar system.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] While his model maintained circular orbits, it was sufficient to calculate the size of planetary orbits and their period.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The appealing simplicity of Copernican astronomy led to its adoption among astronomers even before it was confirmed by Galileo's telescopic observations in the 1600s.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Sometime around 1608 the telescope was invented and by 1610, Galileo Galilei observed phases on the planet Venus similar to those of the Moon, supporting the heliocentric model.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Around the same time the heliocentric model was organized quantitatively by Johannes Kepler.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Analyzing two decades of careful observations by Tycho Brahe, Kepler devised a system that described the details of the motion of the planets around the Sun.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] While Kepler discarded the uniform circular motion of Copernicus in favor of elliptical motion, he did not succeed in formulating a theory behind the laws he wrote down.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] It was Isaac Newton, with his invention of celestial dynamics and his law of gravitation, who finally explained the motions of the planets.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Newton also developed the reflecting telescope.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Newton, in collaboration with Richard Bentley proposed that stars are like the Sun only much further away.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The new telescopes also altered ideas about stars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] By 1610 Galileo discovered that the band of light crossing the sky at night that we call the Milky Way was composed of numerous stars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In 1668 James Gregory compared the luminosity of Jupiter to Sirius to estimate its distance at over 83,000 AU.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The English astronomer John Flamsteed, Britain's first Astronomer Royal, catalogued over 3000 stars but the data were published against his wishes in 1712.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The astronomer William Herschel made a detailed catalog of nebulosity and clusters, and in 1781 discovered the planet Uranus, the first new planet found.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Friedrich Bessel developed the technique of stellar parallax in 1838 but it was so difficult to apply that only about 100 stars were measured by 1900.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] During the 18–19th centuries, the study of the three-body problem by Leonhard Euler, Alexis Claude Clairaut, and Jean le Rond d'Alembert led to more accurate predictions about the motions of the Moon and planets.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] This work was further refined by Joseph-Louis Lagrange and Pierre Simon Laplace, allowing the masses of the planets and moons to be estimated from their perturbations.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Significant advances in astronomy came about with the introduction of new technology, including the spectroscope and astrophotography.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In 1814–15, Joseph von Fraunhofer discovered some 574 dark lines in the spectrum of the sun and of other stars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In 1859, Gustav Kirchhoff ascribed these lines to the presence of different elements.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In the late 1700s William Herschel mapped the distribution of stars in different directions from Earth, concluding that the universe consisted of the Sun near the center of disk of stars, the Milky Way.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] After John Michell demonstrated that stars differ in intrinsic luminosity and after Herschel's own observations with more powerful telescopes that additional stars appeared in all directions, astronomers began to consider that some of the fuzzy spiral nebulae were distant *island Universes*.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The existence of galaxies, including the Earth's galaxy, the Milky Way, as a group of stars was only demonstrated in the 20th century.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In 1912, Henrietta Leavitt discovered Cepheid variable stars with well-defined, periodic luminosity changes which can be used to fix the star's true luminosity which then becomes an accurate tool for distance estimates.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Using Cepheid variable stars, Harlow Shapley constructed the first accurate map of the Milky Way.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Using the Hooker Telescope, Edwin Hubble identified Cepheid variables in several spiral nebulae and in 1922–1923 proved conclusively that Andromeda Nebula and Triangulum among others, were entire galaxies outside our own, thus proving that the universe consists of a multitude of galaxies.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Albert Einstein's 1917 publication of general relativity began the modern era of theoretical models of the universe as a whole.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In 1922, Alexander Friedman published simplified models for the universe showing static, expanding and contracting solutions.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In 1929 Hubble published observations that the galaxies are all moving away from Earth with a velocity proportional to distance, a relation now known as Hubble's law.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] This relation is expected if the universe is expanding.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The consequence that the universe was once very dense and hot, a Big Bang concept expounded by Georges Lemaître in 1927, was discussed but no experimental evidence was available to support it.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] From the 1940s on, nuclear reaction rates under high density conditions were studied leading to the development of a successful model of big bang nucleosynthesis in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Then in 1965 cosmic microwave background radiation was discovered, cementing the evidence for the Big Bang.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astrophysics predicted the existence of objects such as black holes and neutron stars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] These have been used to explain phenomena such as quasars and pulsars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Space telescopes have enabled measurements in parts of the electromagnetic spectrum normally blocked or blurred by the atmosphere.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The LIGO project detected evidence of gravitational waves in 2015.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Observational astronomy relies on many different wavelengths of electromagnetic radiation and the forms of astronomy are categorized according to the corresponding region of the electromagnetic spectrum on which the observations are made.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Specific information on these subfields is given below.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Radio astronomy uses radiation with long wavelengths, mainly between 1 millimeter and 15 meters (frequencies from 20 MHz to 300 GHz), far outside the visible range.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Hydrogen, otherwise an invisible gas, produces a spectral line at 21 cm (1420 MHz) which is observable at radio wavelengths.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Objects observable at radio wavelengths include interstellar gas, pulsars, fast radio bursts, supernovae, and active galactic nuclei.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Infrared astronomy detects infrared radiation with wavelengths longer than red visible light, outside the range of our vision.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The infrared spectrum is useful for studying objects that are too cold to radiate visible light, such as planets, circumstellar disks or nebulae whose light is blocked by dust.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The longer wavelengths of infrared can penetrate clouds of dust that block visible light, allowing the observation of young stars embedded in molecular clouds and the cores of galaxies.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Observations from the Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer (WISE) have been particularly effective at unveiling numerous galactic protostars and their host star clusters.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] With the exception of infrared wavelengths close to visible light, such radiation is heavily absorbed by the atmosphere, or masked, as the atmosphere itself produces significant infrared emission.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Consequently, infrared observatories have to be located in high, dry places on Earth or in space.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Some molecules radiate strongly in the infrared.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] This allows the study of the chemistry of space.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The James Webb Space Telescope senses infrared radiation to detect very distant galaxies.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Visible light from these galaxies was emitted billions of years ago and the expansion of the universe shifted the light in to the infrared range.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] By studying these distant galaxies astronomers hope to learn about the formation of the first galaxies.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Historically, optical astronomy, which has been also called visible light astronomy, is the oldest form of astronomy.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Images of observations were originally drawn by hand.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In the late 19th century and most of the 20th century, images were made using photographic equipment.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Modern images are made using digital detectors, particularly using charge-coupled devices (CCDs) and recorded on modern medium.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Although visible light itself extends from approximately 380 to 700 nm that same equipment can be used to observe some near-ultraviolet and near-infrared radiation.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Ultraviolet astronomy employs ultraviolet wavelengths which are absorbed by the Earth's atmosphere, requiring observations from the upper atmosphere or from space.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Ultraviolet astronomy is best suited to the study of thermal radiation and spectral emission lines from hot blue OB stars that are very bright at these wavelengths.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] X-ray astronomy uses X-radiation, produced by extremely hot and high-energy processes.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Since X-rays are absorbed by the Earth's atmosphere, observations must be performed at high altitude, such as from balloons, rockets, or specialized satellites.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] X-ray sources include X-ray binaries, supernova remnants, clusters of galaxies, and active galactic nuclei.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Since the Sun's surface is relatively cool, X-ray images of the Sun and other stars give valuable information on the hot solar corona.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Gamma ray astronomy observes astronomical objects at the shortest wavelengths (highest energy) of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Gamma rays may be observed directly by satellites such as the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory, or by specialized telescopes called atmospheric Cherenkov telescopes.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Cherenkov telescopes do not detect the gamma rays directly but instead detect the flashes of visible light produced when gamma rays are absorbed by the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Gamma-ray astronomy provides information on the origin of cosmic rays, possible annihilation events for dark matter, relativistic particles outflows from active galactic nuclei (AGN), and, using AGN as distant sources, properties of intergalactic space.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Gamma-ray bursts, which radiate transiently, are extremely energetic events, and are the brightest (most luminous) phenomena in the universe.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Some events originating from great distances may be observed from the Earth using systems that do not rely on electromagnetic radiation.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In neutrino astronomy, astronomers use heavily shielded underground facilities such as SAGE, GALLEX, and Kamioka II/III for the detection of neutrinos.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The vast majority of the neutrinos streaming through the Earth originate from the Sun, but 24 neutrinos were also detected from supernova 1987A.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Cosmic rays, which consist of very high energy particles (atomic nuclei) that can decay or be absorbed when they enter the Earth's atmosphere, result in a cascade of secondary particles which can be detected by current observatories.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Gravitational-wave astronomy employs gravitational-wave detectors to collect observational data about distant massive objects.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] A few observatories have been constructed, such as the *Laser Interferometer Gravitational Observatory* LIGO.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] LIGO made its first detection on 14 September 2015, observing gravitational waves from a binary black hole.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] A second gravitational wave was detected on 26 December 2015 and additional observations should continue but gravitational waves require extremely sensitive instruments.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The combination of observations made using electromagnetic radiation, neutrinos or gravitational waves and other complementary information, is known as multi-messenger astronomy.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] One of the oldest fields in astronomy, and in all of science, is the measurement of the positions of celestial objects known as astrometry.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Historically, accurate knowledge of the positions of the Sun, Moon, planets and stars has been essential in celestial navigation (the use of celestial objects to guide navigation) and in the making of calendars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Careful measurement of the positions of the planets has led to a solid understanding of gravitational perturbations, and an ability to determine past and future positions of the planets with great accuracy, a field known as celestial mechanics.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The measurement of stellar parallax of nearby stars provides a fundamental baseline in the cosmic distance ladder that is used to measure the scale of the Universe.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Parallax measurements of nearby stars provide an absolute baseline for the properties of more distant stars, as their properties can be compared.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Measurements of the radial velocity and proper motion of stars allow astronomers to plot the movement of these systems through the Milky Way galaxy.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Physical cosmology, the study of large-scale structure of the Universe, seeks to understand the formation and evolution of the cosmos.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Fundamental to modern cosmology is the well-accepted theory of the Big Bang, the concept that the universe begin extremely dense and hot, then expanded over the course of 13.8 billion years to its present condition.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The concept of the Big Bang became widely accepted after the discovery of the microwave background radiation in 1965.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Dark matter and dark energy are now thought form 96% of the mass of the Universe.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] For this reason, much effort is expended in trying to understand the physics of these components.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The study of objects outside our galaxy is concerned with the formation and evolution of galaxies, their morphology (description) and classification, the observation of active galaxies, and at a larger scale, the groups and clusters of galaxies.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] These assist the understanding of the large-scale structure of the cosmos.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Galactic astronomy studies galaxies including the Milky Way, a barred spiral galaxy that is a prominent member of the Local Group of galaxies and contains the Solar System.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] It is a rotating mass of gas, dust, stars and other objects, held together by mutual gravitational attraction.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] As the Earth is within the dusty outer arms, large portions of the Milky Way are obscured from view.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Kinematic studies of matter in the Milky Way and other galaxies show there is more mass than can be accounted for by visible matter.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] A dark matter halo appears to dominate the mass, although the nature of this dark matter remains undetermined.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The study of stars and stellar evolution is fundamental to our understanding of the Universe.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The astrophysics of stars has been determined through observation and theoretical understanding; and from computer simulations of the interior.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Aspects studied include star formation in giant molecular clouds; the formation of protostars; and the transition to nuclear fusion and main-sequence stars, carrying out nucleosynthesis.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Further processes studied include stellar evolution, ending either with supernovae or white dwarfs.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The ejection of the outer layers forms a planetary nebula.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The remnant of a supernova is a dense neutron star, or, if the stellar mass was at least three times that of the Sun, a black hole.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Solar astronomy is the study of the Sun, a typical main-sequence dwarf star of stellar class G2 V, and about 4.6 billion years (Gyr) old.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Processes studied by the science include the sunspot cycle, the sun's changes in luminosity, both steady and periodic, and the behavior of the sun's various layers, namely its core with its nuclear fusion, the radiation zone, the convection zone, the photosphere, the chromosphere, and the corona.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Planetary science is the study of the assemblage of planets, moons, dwarf planets, comets, asteroids, and other bodies orbiting the Sun, as well as exoplanets orbiting distant stars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The Solar System has been relatively well-studied, initially through telescopes and then later by spacecraft.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Processes studied include planetary differentiation; the generation of, and effects created by, a planetary magnetic field; and the creation of heat within a planet, such as by collisions, radioactive decay, and tidal heating.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In turn, that heat can drive geologic processes such as volcanism, tectonics, and surface erosion, studied by branches of geology.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astrochemistry is an overlap of astronomy and chemistry.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] It studies the abundance and reactions of molecules in the Universe, and their interaction with radiation.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The word "astrochemistry" may be applied to both the Solar System and the interstellar medium.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Studies in this field contribute for example to the understanding of the formation of the Solar System.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astrobiology (or exobiology) studies the origin of life and its development other than on earth.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] It considers whether extraterrestrial life exists, and how humans can detect it if it does.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] It makes use of astronomy, biochemistry, geology, microbiology, physics, and planetary science to investigate the possibility of life on other worlds and help recognize biospheres that might be different from that on Earth.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The origin and early evolution of life is an inseparable part of the discipline of astrobiology.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astronomy and astrophysics have developed interdisciplinary links with other major scientific fields.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Archaeoastronomy is the study of ancient or traditional astronomies in their cultural context, using archaeological and anthropological evidence.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astrostatistics is the application of statistics to the analysis of large quantities of observational astrophysical data.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] As "forensic astronomy", finally, methods from astronomy have been used to solve problems of art history and occasionally of law.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astronomy is one of the sciences to which amateurs can contribute the most.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Collectively, amateur astronomers observe celestial objects and phenomena, sometimes with consumer-level equipment or equipment that they build themselves.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Common targets include the Sun, the Moon, planets, stars, comets, meteor showers, and deep-sky objects such as star clusters, galaxies, and nebulae.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Astronomy clubs throughout the world have programs to help their members set up and run observational programs such as to observe all the objects in the Messier (110 objects) or Herschel 400 catalogues.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Most amateurs work at visible wavelengths, but some have experimented with wavelengths outside the visible spectrum.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] The pioneer of amateur radio astronomy, Karl Jansky, discovered a radio source at the centre of the Milky Way.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Some amateur astronomers use homemade telescopes or radio telescopes originally built for astronomy research (*e.g.* the One-Mile Telescope).
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Amateurs can make occultation measurements to refine the orbits of minor planets.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] They can discover comets, and perform regular observations of variable stars.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Improvements in digital technology have allowed amateurs to make advances in astrophotography.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] In the 21st century, there remain important unanswered questions in astronomy.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Some are cosmic in scope: for example, what are the dark matter and dark energy that dominate the evolution and fate of the cosmos?
[src:astronomy/astronomy] What will be the ultimate fate of the universe?
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Why is the abundance of lithium in the cosmos four times lower than predicted by the standard Big Bang model?
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Others pertain to more specific classes of phenomena.
[src:astronomy/astronomy] For example, is the Solar System normal or atypical?
[src:astronomy/astronomy] What is the origin of the stellar mass spectrum, i.e. why do astronomers observe the same distribution of stellar masses—the initial mass function—regardless of initial conditions?
[src:astronomy/astronomy] Likewise, questions remain about the formation of the first galaxies, the origin of supermassive black holes, the source of ultra-high-energy cosmic rays, and whether there is other life in the Universe, especially other intelligent life.
